[[File:Gringo Gazette.jpg|right|thumb|A woman reading the English-language ''[[Gringo Gazette]]'' in [[Baja California Sur]], Mexico]] {{other uses}} {{Wiktionary|gringo}} A '''''gringo''''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|g|r|ɪ|ŋ|g|oʊ|}}, {{IPA-es|ˈɡɾiŋɡo|lang}}, {{IPA-pt|ˈɡɾĩɡu|lang}}) or '''''gringa''''' (female) is someone considered a foreigner from the perspective of [[Hispanophone|Spanish]] and [[Portuguese-speaking]] countries in [[Latin America]]. In [[Spanish language|Spanish]] and English, ''gringo'' usually refers to an [[English language|English-speaking]] foreigner, especially one from the [[United States]]. It often carries a derogatory connotation, particularly in English. Possible other connotations may include [[monolingualism]], a lack of understanding of [[Hispanic]] culture, and [[blond]] hair.<ref>English dictionaries: * {{cite web|title=gringo|url=http://dictionary.cambridge.org/us/dictionary/british/gringo?q=gringo|work=Cambridge Dictionaries Online|publisher=Cambridge University|accessdate=20 February 2014|quote=used in Latin American countries to refer to people from the US or other English-speaking countries}} * {{cite web|title=gringo|url=http://www.thefreedictionary.com/gringo|work=definition of gringo|publisher=The Free Dictionary|accessdate=20 February 2014|quote=Used as a sometimes disparaging term for a foreigner in Latin America, especially an American or English person.}} * {{cite web|title=gringo|url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/gringo|work=Merriam-Webster Dictionary|accessdate=20 February 2014|quote=a foreigner in Spain or Latin America especially when of English or American origin;}} * {{cite web|title=Gringo|url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/gringo|publisher=Dictionary.com|accessdate=20 February 2014|quote=(in Latin America or Spain) a foreigner, especially one of U.S. or British descent.}} Spanish dictionaries: * {{cite web|title=gringo, ga|url=http://clave.smdiccionarios.com/app.php|work=SM Diccionarios|accessdate=20 February 2014|quote=Persona nacida en los Estados Unidos de América (país americano)}} * {{cite web|title=gringo, ga.|url=http://lema.rae.es/drae/|work=Diccionario de la lengua española|publisher=Real Academia Española|accessdate=20 February 2014|quote=Extranjero, especialmente de habla inglesa, y en general hablante de una lengua que no sea la española; Am. Mer., Cuba, El Salv., Hond. y Nic. estadounidense.}} * {{cite web |title=gringo - Definición - WordReference.com |url=http://www.wordreference.com/definicion/gringo |website=www.wordreference.com |accessdate=1 December 2018 |language=es|quote=Persona nacida en Estados Unidos, en especial la de habla inglesa.}}</ref> The word was originally used in [[Spain]] to denote any foreign, non-native speakers of Spanish.
According to the ''[[Oxford English Dictionary]]'', the first recorded use in English comes from [[John James Audubon#Marriage and family|John Woodhouse Audubon]]'s ''Western Journal of 1849–1850'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/audubonswesternj00audufo|title=Audubon's western journal, 1849-1850; being the ms. record of a trip from New York to Texas, and an overland journey through Mexico and Arizona to the gold fields of California|first1=John Woodhouse|last1=Audubon|first2=Maria Rebecca|last2=Audubon|first3=Frank Heywood|last3=Hodder|date=20 September 2017|publisher=Cleveland, A. H. Clark|accessdate=20 September 2017|via=Internet Archive}}</ref><ref name="OED">[http://dictionary.oed.com.dax.lib.unf.edu/cgi/entry/50098913?single=1&query_type=word&queryword=gringo&first=1&max_to_show=10 "Gringo"] From the ''[[Oxford English Dictionary]]''. Retrieved November 28, 2008.</ref> in which Audubon reports that his party was hooted and shouted at and called "Gringoes" while passing through the town of Cerro Gordo, [[Veracruz]].<ref>Audubon, John W. (1906). [https://books.google.com/books?id=HrnMqMrDrSwC&pg=PA100&lpg=PA100&dq=%22We+were+hooted+and+shouted+at+as+we+passed+through%22&source=web&ots=sT9rK4S4d5&sig=VYyB9FXz96OdM5vMDvzPhfkPk1Q&hl=en&sa=X&oi=book_result&resnum=2&ct=result#PPA99,M1 ''Audubon's Western Journal 1849–1850''], p. 100. Cleveland: Arthur H. Clark Company.</ref>
==Etymology== The word ''gringo'' originally referred to any kind of foreigner. It was first recorded in 1787 in the Spanish ''Diccionario castellano con las voces de Ciencias y Artes'':<ref name=Varela>Beatriz Varela, "Ethnic Nicknames of Spanish Origin", in {{cite book|last=Rodríguez González|first=Félix|title=Spanish Loanwords in the English Language: A Tendency Towards Hegemony Reversal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=09NEuGHh2R8C&pg=PA143|year=1996|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|isbn=978-3-11-014845-9|page=143}} (''[https://books.google.com/books?id=5XtdDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA143 backup link]'')</ref><ref name="First">{{cite book|author=Esteban Terreros y Pando (S.I.)|title=Diccionario castellano con las voces de ciencias y artes y sus correspondientes en las tres lenguas francesa, latina é italiana: E-O|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1SU3vKYK7pcC&pg=PA240|year=1787|publisher=en la imprenta de la Viuda de Ibarra, Hijos y Compañia|page=240}}</ref>{{efn|"Castilian Dictionary including the Words of the Sciences and the Arts, and their Correspondents in Three Languages: French, Latin, and Italian"}}
{{quote|GRINGOS, llaman en Málaga a los extranjeros, que tienen cierta especie de acento, que los priva de una locución fácil, y natural Castellana; y en Madrid dan el mismo, y por la misma causa con particularidad a los Irlandeses. ''Gringos'' is what, in Malaga, they call foreigners who have a certain type of accent that prevents them from speaking Castilian easily and naturally; and in Madrid they give the same name, and for the same reason, in particular to the Irish.}}
The most likely theory is that it originates from ''griego'' ('Greek'), used in the same way as the English phrase "it's [[Greek to me]]".<ref name=snopes>{{cite web|url=https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/gringo/|title=Etymology of Gringo|date=17 April 2011|publisher=|accessdate=20 September 2017}}</ref><ref name="Tschudi1847">{{cite book|author=Johann Jakob von Tschudi|authorlink=Johann Jakob von Tschudi|title=Travels in Peru, During the Years 1838-1842: On the Coast, in the Sierra, Across the Cordilleras and the Andes, Into the Primeval Forests|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DrECAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA122|year=1847|publisher=D. Bogue|page=122}}</ref> Spanish is known to have used Greek as a stand-in for incomprehensibility, though now less common, such as in the phrase ''hablar en griego'' (lit. 'to speak Greek'). The 1817 ''Nuevo diccionario francés-español'',{{efn|"New French–Spanish Dictionary"}} for example, gives ''gringo'' and ''griego'' as synonyms in this context:<ref name="Montpalau1817">{{cite book|author1=Antonio de Capmany y de Montpalau|author2=Imprenta de Sancha (Madrid)|title=Nuevo diccionario francés-español: en este van enmendados, corregidos, mejorados, y enriquecidos considerablemente los de Gattel, y Cormon|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rRDCjVSNUeYC&pg=RA1-PA448|year=1817|publisher=Imprenta de Sancha|location=Under ''Hebreu'' and ''Parler''|pages=448, 628}}</ref> {{verse translation|... hablar en griego, en guirigay, en gringo. Gringo, griego: aplícase a lo que se dice o escribe sin entenderse. |... to speak in Greek, in gibberish, in gringo. Gringo, Greek : applied to what is said or written but not understood.}}
This derivation requires two steps: ''griego'' > ''grigo'', and ''grigo'' > ''gringo''. Corominas notes that while the first change is common in Spanish (e.g. ''[[wikt:priesa|priesa]]'' to ''[[wikt:prisa|prisa]]''), there is no perfect analogy for the second, save in [[Old French]] (''Gregoire'' to ''Grigoire'' to ''Gringoire'').<ref name=cor>''Griego'' at ''[[Diccionario crítico etimológico de la lengua castellana]]'', Vol. II, pag. 784 (25), [[Joan Corominas]], Francke Verlag, Berna, 1954, {{ISBN|978-84-249-1361-8}}</ref> However, there are other Spanish words whose colloquial form contains an [[epenthesis|epenthetic]] ''n'', such as ''[[wikt:gordiflón|gordiflón]]'' and ''[[wikt:gordinflón|gordinflón]]'' ('chubby'), and ''[[wikt:Cochinchina|Cochinchina]]'' and ''[[wikt:Conchinchina|Conchinchina]]'' ('South Vietnam'). It is also possible that the final form was influenced by the word ''[[jeringonza]]'', a game like [[Pig Latin]] also used to mean "gibberish".<ref name=Varela/>
Alternatively, it has been suggested that ''gringo'' could derive from the [[Caló language]], the language of the [[Romani people in Spain|Romani people of Spain]], as a variant of the hypothetical *''peregringo'', 'peregrine', 'wayfarer', 'stranger'.<ref>Irving L. Allen, ''The Language of Ethnic Conflict: Social Organization and Lexical Culture'', 1983, {{ISBN|0-231-05557-9}}, p. 129</ref><ref name="sayers">William Sayers, [https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/14753820902937946 "An Unnoticed Early Attestation of gringo 'Foreigner': Implications for Its Origin"], in the ''Bulletin of Spanish Studies'' '''86''':3:323 (2009)</ref>
===Folk etymologies=== There are several conjectures within [[folk etymology]] that purport to derive the origin of ''gringo'' from word coincidences.
Many theories date the word to the [[Mexican–American War]] (1846–1848), as a result of American troops singing a song which began with "Green grows..." such as "[[Green Grow the Rushes, O]]", "[[Green Grow the Lilacs]]", and various others.<ref name=snopes/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.voltairenet.org/article120522.html|title=Origen de la palabra "gringo", por Roberto Ponce|first=Roberto Ponce,Red|last=Voltaire|publisher=|accessdate=20 September 2017}}</ref> Other theories involve locals yelling "Green, go!" at invading American soldiers (sometimes in conflicts other than the Mexican–American War), in reference to their supposedly green uniforms.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Colorful Origin Stories of "Gringo" |url=https://www.visualthesaurus.com/cm/wordroutes/the-colorful-origin-stories-of-gringo/ |website=www.visualthesaurus.com |accessdate=14 November 2018}}</ref> Another derives it from Irish "[[Erin go bragh]]" ("Ireland forever"), which served as the motto for [[Saint Patrick's Battalion]] who fought alongside the Mexican army.<ref name="Nipongo2001">{{cite book|author=Nikito Nipongo|title=Perlas|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=huZsN0oQOkUC&pg=PA24|year=2001|publisher=LD Books|isbn=968-5270-38-4|page=24}}</ref><ref name="Hernández1925">{{cite book|author=José Hernández|title="Martín Fierro", comentado y anotado|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=dmgCAAAAMAAJ&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Erin+go+bragh|year=1925|page=421}}</ref>
==Modern usage== ===Spain=== In modern [[Spain]], the word ''gringo'' is understood but rarely used. Nowadays, the closest equivalent vernacular is ''[[guiri]]'', or ''yanqui'' ([[yankee]]) for [[United States|U.S. Americans]] of any regional origin, including Southerners. ''Gringo'' is only heard among [[Latin America]]n immigrants or native Spaniards imitating their speech for fun or solidarity. These terms can be merely descriptive, derogatory or friendly depending on the context and situation.
===Argentina=== The word ''gringo'' is mostly used in rural areas following the original Spanish meaning. ''Gringo'' in Argentina was used to refer to non-Spanish European immigrants who first established agricultural colonies in the country. The word was used for Swiss, German, Polish, Italian and other immigrants, but since the Italian immigrants were the larger group, the word used to be mostly linked to [[Italians]] in the ''[[lunfardo]]'' [[argot]].<ref>http://www.fhuc.unl.edu.ar/portalgringo/crear/gringa/elportal/pdf/editoriales/gringo1.pdf</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=La Barcelona Argentina: migrantes, obreros y militantes en Rosario, 1870-1912|last=Falcón|first=Ricardo|publisher=Laborde Editor|year=2005|isbn=9879459962|location=|pages=221|language=Spanish}}</ref> It has also found use in the intermittent exercise [[Gringo-Gaucho]] between [[Argentine Naval Aviation]] and [[USN]] aircraft carriers.
===Brazil=== In [[Brazil]], the word gringo means simply foreigner, and has no connection to any physical characteristics or specific countries. Unlike most Hispanic American countries, in which gringo is never used to refer to other Latin Americans, in Brazil there is no such distinction in the use of the term. Most foreign [[Association Football|footballers]] in the [[Brasileirão|Brazilian Championship]] that came from other Latin American countries are nevertheless referred as "gringos" by the sport media<ref>{{cite web|title=gringo footballers in Brazil 2015|url=http://www.lancenet.com.br/minuto/Confira-gringos-pintar-futebol-brasileiro_0_1268273211.html|publisher=Lance Net|accessdate=10 February 2015|quote=The word being used for Hispanic American footballers in Brazil.|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20150211075055/http://www.lancenet.com.br/minuto/Confira-gringos-pintar-futebol-brasileiro_0_1268273211.html|archivedate=11 February 2015|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=gringo footballers in Brazil 2015 (ESPN)|url=http://espn.uol.com.br/post/467443_conheca-gringos-que-podem-reforcar-times-brasileiros-na-temporada-2015|publisher=Lance Net|accessdate=10 February 2015|quote=The word being used for Hispanic American footballers in Brazil.}}</ref> and by sport fans.<ref>{{cite web|title=Expanded "gringo" limit in Brazilian Championship|url=http://doentesporfutebol.com.br/2014/07/novo-limite-faz-numero-de-gringos-aumentar-no-brasil/|accessdate=10 February 2015|quote=The word being used by a fan as a synonym of foreigner in the Brazilian Championship.}}</ref> Tourists are called gringos, and there is no differentiation in the use of the term for Latin Americans or people from other regions, like Europe.<ref>{{cite web|title=turistas gringos|url=http://www.redebomdia.com.br/noticia/detalhe/69817/torcedores-gringos-elogiam-e-reclamam-do-brasil|publisher=Terra|accessdate=10 February 2015|quote=The word being used for European and Latin American tourists in Brazil.|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160125230641/http://www.redebomdia.com.br/noticia/detalhe/69817/torcedores-gringos-elogiam-e-reclamam-do-brasil|archivedate=25 January 2016|df=}}</ref>
As the word has no connection to physical appearance in Brazil, [[Black people|black African]] or [[African Americans|African American]] foreigners are also called gringos,<ref>{{cite web|title=Cameroon gringos|url=http://migramundo.com/2014/06/09/camaroes-conquista-copa-gringos-mas-o-futebol-e-os-migrantes-saem-como-vencedores/|publisher=Migra Mundo|accessdate=10 February 2015|quote=Black immigrants from Cameroon play the "Copa Gringos" in Brazil.|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141202181131/http://migramundo.com/2014/06/09/camaroes-conquista-copa-gringos-mas-o-futebol-e-os-migrantes-saem-como-vencedores/|archivedate=2 December 2014|df=}}</ref> unlike some other countries in which the term implies fair skin. Popularly used terms for fair-skinned and blond people are generally based in specific nationalities, like "alemão" (i.e., [[germans|German]]), "russo" ([[Russians (ethnic group)|Russian]]) or, in some regions, "galego" ([[Galician people|Galician]])<ref>{{Cite web|title = Significado de "galego"|url = http://www.dicionarioinformal.com.br/galego/|website = www.dicionarioinformal.com.br|access-date = 2016-01-25}}</ref> which are used for both Brazilians<ref>{{cite web|title=Brazilian reality show celebrity nicknamed Alemão|url=http://extra.globo.com/famosos/ex-bbb-diego-alemao-reaparece-irreconhecivel-durante-festa-no-rio-15147097.html|publisher=Extra|accessdate=10 February 2015|quote=The word Alemão as nickname for non-German Brazilian.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Brazilian footballer nicknamed Alemão|url=http://terceirotempo.bol.uol.com.br/que-fim-levou/alemao-1582|publisher=Bol|accessdate=10 February 2015|quote=The word Alemão as nickname for non-German Brazilian Footballer.}}</ref> and foreigners<ref>{{cite web|title=Complexo do Alemão|url=http://www.encontrapenharj.com.br/penha/complexo-do-alemao.shtml|publisher=Encontra Penha RJ|accessdate=10 February 2015|quote=The word Alemão as nickname for Polish Immigrant Leonard Kaczmarkiewicz eventually lead a whole community to be known as Complexo do Alemão(German's Complex).}}</ref> with such characteristics, regardless of their real ethnic origins.
===Activism=== In 1969, [[Jose Angel Gutierrez]] (one of the leaders of the [[Mexican American Youth Organization]]) said his and MAYO's use of the term, rather than referring to non-Latinos, referred to people or institutions with policies or attitudes that reflect racism and violence.<ref>{{cite web |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070917033004/http://www.uta.edu/public-affairs/official-statements/stories.php?id=2133 |archive-date=17 September 2007 |url=http://www.uta.edu/public-affairs/official-statements/stories.php?id=2133 |website=UTA.edu |first=Kemper |last=Diehl |date=26 April 2006 |title=STATEMENTS BY JOSE ANGEL GUTIERREZ, SAN ANTONIO EVENING NEWS, APRIL 11, 1969 |quote=A person or an institution who has a certain policy or program or attitudes that reflect bigotry, racism, discord and prejudice and violence.}}</ref>
==Other uses== In [[Mexican cuisine]], a ''[[gringas|gringa]]'' is a flour tortilla with [[al pastor]] pork meat with cheese, heated on a ''[[comal (cookware)|comal]]'' and optionally served with a ''salsa de chile'' (chilli sauce). The name is either a reference to the white flour used,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.lamag.com/digestblog/tacopedia-a-complete-taco-encyclopedia-of-l-a/|title=Tacos in LA: A Complete Taco Encyclopedia of L.A.|last=|first=|date=July 24, 2015|work=Los Angeles Magazine|access-date=February 10, 2018|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=en-US}}</ref> or its creation, when two women from the United States asked a Mexico City ''[[taquería]]'' for a Mexican dish but disliked corn tortillas.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}
