__notoc__ {{Use mdy dates|date=January 2016}} [[File:Howdy Doody peanut gallery circa 1940 1950s.JPG|thumb|325px|Howdy Doody peanut gallery {{circa|1940}} to the 1950s]]
A '''peanut gallery''' was, in the days of [[vaudeville]], a nickname for the cheapest and ostensibly rowdiest seats in the theater, the occupants of which were often known to [[Heckler|heckle]] the performers.<ref name=TSD_1999>{{cite web|last=Rowland|first=Ian|title= What's the origin of the expression ‘peanut gallery’?|url = http://www.straightdope.com/columns/read/1538/whats-the-origin-of-the-expression-peanut-gallery |work= The Straight Dope| accessdate= March 28, 2013| authorlink = Ian Rowland |date=April 1999}}</ref> The least expensive snack served at the theatre would often be [[peanut]]s, which the patrons would sometimes throw at the performers on stage to convey their disapproval. Phrases such as "no comments from the peanut gallery" or "quiet in the peanut gallery" are extensions of the name.<ref name =TSD_1999 />
In 1943 the ''[[Howdy Doody]]'' children's radio show adopted the name for its live audience of children.<ref name=Smith_2002>{{cite book|last=Smith | first =Andrew F.|title=Peanuts: The Illustrious History of the Goober Pea|year=2002|publisher=University of Illinois Press|isbn= 978-0-252-02553-2 |page=129|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=JbOsI9RG8fYC&lpg=PA129}}</ref> Howdy Doody is most remembered for its later transition to television, which continued the Peanut Gallery audience, now on camera.
==In popular culture==
In recent times, the term has taken on new meanings with the advent of [[Social networking service|social networks]] and online [[chat room]]s. "Peanut gallery" may also refer to the stream of open comments visible on certain types of blogs.<ref name = "BIO230 Blog Archives">{{cite web| work = BIO230 | type = Web log | title = Bacteriophages | publisher = Word press |date=Fall 2010 | url = http://bio230fall2010.wordpress.com/tag/bacteriophage/|accessdate=May 31, 2013}}</ref>
A similar term was introduced to Brazilian football by coach [[Luis Felipe Scolari]]. He called [[Sociedade Esportiva Palmeiras|Palmeiras]]' complaining audience that sat in the closest seats "''Turma do Amendoim''" ("peanut gang").<ref>{{cite news| publisher = Folha da manhã | title=Felipão criou o apelido "Turma do Amendoim" no Palmeiras; leia trecho |trans-title=Felipão created the ‘Peanut gang’ nickname: read passage | url= http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/folha/esporte/ult92u649799.shtml|accessdate=March 28, 2013 |newspaper=Folha de S. Paulo | date=November 9, 2009|agency=Folha Online| language= Portuguese}}</ref>
